{"type":"assistant","message":{"model":"claude-haiku-4-5-20251001","id":"msg_018i3qqcYKVAgFPyZ6F8pBYk","type":"message","role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"text","text":"Looking at this git summarization tool, I need to determine what test infrastructure level is required to catch real failures in each behavior. The key distinction is between:\n- **Mocking git output** (Unit/Integration) vs. **real subprocess calls to git** (System)\n- **Real local git repos** (Integration level as filesystem resource) vs. **actual `subprocess.run()` calls** (System)\n\nLet me reason through each behavior:\n\n---\n\n## Behavior 1: Renamed files in own category\n\n**Real failure modes:**\n- Tool doesn't call git with rename-detection flags (e.g., `-M`)\n- Tool's parsing misses \"R\" status in git output\n- Tool counts renames as deleted+added\n\n**Why System is minimum:** Mocking git output like `R100\\told\\tnew` tests only the parsing logic. Real failures are in how the tool constructs git commands and handles git's actual behavior. A Unit test wouldn't catch \"forgot the `-M` flag\" bugs.\n\n**Test description:** Create a real git repo, stage a file rename, run the tool, verify it appears only in the \"renamed\" category with correct count, not in both \"deleted\" and \"added.\"\n\n---\n\n## Behavior 2: Binary files don't crash; counted correctly\n\n**Real failure modes:**\n- Tool crashes when git output includes binary file markers\n- Tool mishandles binary diff output\n- Binary files miscounted\n\n**Why System is minimum:** Git's actual output for binary files (truncation, special markers) can't be fully predicted without running real git. Mocking binary output might hide edge cases.\n\n**Test description:** Initialize a real git repo, add actual binary files (images, PDFs), make changes, run tool, verify: (1) no crash, (2) binary files counted correctly.\n\n---\n\n## Behavior 3: Empty repository produces empty report, not error\n\n**Real failure modes:**\n- Tool doesn't handle `git log` returning nothing\n- Tool crashes on git's error message for empty repo\n- Tool returns error instead of empty output\n\n**Why System is minimum:** The exact error/output from git on an empty repo varies by context. Real git behavior is needed.\n\n**Test description:** Create a real git repo with `git init` but no commits, run the tool, verify empty/clean output, no errors or warnings.\n\n---\n\n## Behavior 4: Counts match actual change history\n\n**Real failure modes:**\n- Tool miscounts files across commits\n- Tool misses files in certain states\n- Tool double-counts or misses categories\n\n**Why System is minimum:** This is the core functionality. Verifying counts match history requires a real repo with known commits. Mocking would hide bugs where parsing or category logic breaks on real repos.\n\n**Test description:** Create a real git repo with known sequence of changes (add 3 files, modify 2, delete 1, rename 1), run tool, verify counts exactly match (3 added, 1 renamed, 1 deleted, 2 modified) and don't overlap.\n\n---\n\n## Behavior 5: Output identical for staged vs. unstaged\n\n**Real failure modes:**\n- Tool calls different git commands for staged (e.g., `git diff --cached`) vs. unstaged (e.g., `git diff`)\n- Parsing differs based on which command's output is used\n- Tool picks wrong state by default\n\n**Why System is minimum:** This requires setting up real git state (staged files), then unstaging, then verifying identical output. Only real subprocess calls expose bugs in which git command is chosen.\n\n**Test description:** Create real git repo, stage changes (add file, modify file), run tool, record output. Unstage same changes (or reset), run tool again, verify output is identical.\n\n---"}],"stop_reason":null,"stop_sequence":null,"usage":{"input_tokens":10,"cache_creation_input_tokens":13347,"cache_read_input_tokens":0,"cache_creation":{"ephemeral_5m_input_tokens":0,"ephemeral_1h_input_tokens":13347},"output_tokens":4,"service_tier":"stan